<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is hexadecimal?", answer: "Hexadecimal (hex) is a base-16 number system that uses digits 0-9 and letters A-F to represent values. Each hex digit represents 4 bits, so two hex digits represent one byte (8 bits). Hexadecimal is widely used in computing because it provides a compact, human-readable representation of binary data. For example, the byte 11111111 in binary is FF in hex and 255 in decimal." },
  { question: "What is ASCII?", answer: "ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange) is a character encoding standard that maps 128 characters to numeric values 0-127. It includes uppercase and lowercase English letters, digits 0-9, punctuation marks, and control characters. Each ASCII character fits in 7 bits, with the 8th bit traditionally used for parity. ASCII forms the foundation of modern text encoding standards like UTF-8." },
  { question: "How do I convert hex to text?", answer: "To convert hex to text, take each pair of hex digits, convert it to its decimal value, then look up the corresponding ASCII character. For example, 48 65 6C 6C 6F converts to Hello because 48 hex is 72 decimal (H), 65 hex is 101 decimal (e), 6C hex is 108 decimal (l), and 6F hex is 111 decimal (o). This tool does this conversion instantly." },
  { question: "What are the different hex formats?", answer: "Hex can be written in several formats: spaced pairs (48 65 6C), compact without spaces (48656C), with 0x prefix (0x48 0x65 0x6C), or with backslash-x escape (\\x48\\x65\\x6C). Spaced pairs are the most readable. Compact format is used for hash values and color codes. The 0x prefix is used in programming languages like C and JavaScript. The backslash-x format is used in string literals." },
  { question: "When is hex encoding useful?", answer: "Hex encoding is useful for examining binary file contents, debugging network protocols, working with cryptographic hashes and checksums, defining colors in CSS (e.g., #FF0000 for red), analyzing memory dumps, and embedding binary data in source code. It provides a readable way to represent binary data that would otherwise be unintelligible as raw bytes." }
]) %>

